                            <comment id="14029416" author="tgraves" created="Thu, 12 Jun 2014 17:07:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;On yarn when I run pyspark it kills the executors after a single action.  Perhaps this is caused by this same issue. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This could be a much bigger deal on yarn since when it kills the executors, it has to go back to the resource manager to get more containers.  This is an aweful lot of thrashing of containers and could cause major headaches.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14044981" author="joshrosen" created="Thu, 26 Jun 2014 18:23:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The &quot;Python daemon -&amp;gt; multiple workers&quot; architecture was motivated by the high cost of forking a JVM with a large heap, so this issue could also lead to performance problems if we attempt to re-launch the daemon once a huge amount of data has been cached in the Spark worker JVM.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
